<lg id="t.6.1.15.a1" type="proverb" n="15.a1"><p id="t6115.p1" n="1" corresp="c6115.A.15.a1.1">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 15 Sec. A 1</note>
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.a2" type="proverb" n="15.a2"><p id="t6115.p2" n="2" corresp="c6115.A.15.a2.2">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 15 Sec. A 2</note>
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.a3" type="proverb" n="15.a3"><p id="t6115.p3" n="3-4" corresp="c6115.A.15.a3.3">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 15 Sec. A 3A</note>
Then, when you shout like a fool, someone should say: <q>Your &X;&X; is a captured donkey!</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.a4" type="proverb" n="15.a4"><p id="t6115.p4" n="5-6" corresp="c6115.A.15.a4.5">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 15 Sec. A 3B</note>
It is an insult to &X;&X;. It is the dignity of the palace.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.a5" type="proverb" n="15.a5"><p id="t6115.p5" n="7" corresp="c6115.A.15.a5.7">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 15 Sec. A 4</note>
The well-wisher is the mother of the refugee.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.a6" type="proverb" n="15.a6"><p id="t6115.p6" n="8-9" corresp="c6115.A.15.a6.8">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 15 Sec. A 5</note>
May the people wish you well. May your god grant what you are in agreement with (?).</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.a7" type="proverb" n="15.a7"><p id="t6115.p7" n="10-11" corresp="c6115.A.15.a7.10">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 15 Sec. A 6</note>
<gap extent="2 lines unclear"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.a8" type="proverb" n="15.a8"><p id="t6115.p8" n="12" corresp="c6115.A.15.a8.12">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 15 Sec. A 7</note>
<gap extent="1 line unclear"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.a9" type="proverb" n="15.a9"><p id="t6115.p9" n="13-15" corresp="c6115.A.15.a9.13">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 15 Sec. A 8; cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.19" from="t.6.1.19.f3">6.1.19.f3</xref></note>
&X;&X; food for his sustenance &X;&X; cut &X;&X;.
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/>
<gap extent="unknown no. of lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="B">
<lg id="t.6.1.15.b1" type="proverb" n="15.b1"><p id="t6115.p10" n="1-2" corresp="c6115.B.15.b1.1">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.14" from="t.6.1.14.4">6.1.14.4</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.16" from="t.6.1.16.c2">6.1.16.c2</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: UM 29-16-519 Seg. A ll. 9-10</xref></note>
The shepherd boy lifts his gaze to you <note lang="eng">i.e. Enlil</note>: <q>May <w type="DN">Enlil</w> look upon the city he has cursed.</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.b2" type="proverb" n="15.b2"><p id="t6115.p11" n="3-4" corresp="c6115.B.15.b2.3">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.14" from="t.6.1.14.5">6.1.14.5</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.16" from="t.6.1.16.c3">6.1.16.c3</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: UM 29-16-519 Seg. A ll. 11-12</xref></note>
The potter lifts his gaze to you: <q>May <w type="DN">Enlil</w> look upon the city he has cursed.</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.b3" type="proverb" n="15.b3"><p id="t6115.p12" n="5-6" corresp="c6115.B.15.b3.5">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: UM 29-16-519 Seg. A ll. 13-14</xref></note>
The gardener lifts his gaze to you: <q>May <w type="DN">Enlil</w> look upon the city he has cursed.</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.b4" type="proverb" n="15.b4"><p id="t6115.p13" n="7" corresp="c6115.B.15.b4.7">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.16" from="t.6.1.16.c4">6.1.16.c4</xref></note>
What will the farmer with his vigilant eye do?</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.b5" type="proverb" n="15.b5"><p id="t6115.p14" n="8-9" corresp="c6115.B.15.b5.8">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.25" from="t.6.1.25.1">6.1.25.1</xref></note>
It rained on the river banks but the dry land did not get a drop.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.b6" type="proverb" n="15.b6"><p id="t6115.p15" n="10-11" corresp="c6115.B.15.b6.10">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.2.3" from="t623.h68">6.2.3: UET 6/2 305</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.3" from="t623.h69">6.2.3: UET 6/2 330</xref></note>
&X;&X; you shouldn't give a lame man a staff. <w type="DN">Enlil</w> is his helper.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.b7" type="proverb" n="15.b7"><p id="t6115.p16" n="12-13" corresp="c6115.B.15.b7.12">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.25" from="t.6.1.25.2">6.1.25.2</xref></note>
The high priest rejected fish, he rejected leeks, and he should also reject the <foreign lang="sux">zag&h;ili</foreign> plant.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.b8" type="proverb" n="15.b8"><p id="t6115.p17" n="14-15" corresp="c6115.B.15.b8.14">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.03" from="t.6.1.03.31">6.1.03.31</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.09" from="t.6.1.09.b1">6.1.09.b1</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.11" from="t.6.1.11.18">6.1.11.18</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.25" from="t.6.1.25.4">6.1.25.4</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.1">6.2.1: Ni 4469 Seg. A ll. 9-12</xref></note>
He started building <w type="DN">Enlil's</w> temple but did not complete it. He built a wall around <w type="SN">Nibru</w>, but &X;&X;
<gap extent="unknown no. of lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="C">
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c1" type="proverb" n="15.c1"><p id="t6115.p18" n="1" corresp="c6115.C.15.c1.1">
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c2" type="proverb" n="15.c2"><p id="t6115.p19" n="2-4" corresp="c6115.C.15.c2.2">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.26" from="t.6.1.26.b3">6.1.26.b3</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.28" from="t.6.1.28.7">6.1.28.7</xref></note>
Let the herdsman whip the ox. Let the shepherd slaughter the sheep. Where there is no toughness, no man can go about his business.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c3" type="proverb" n="15.c3"><p id="t6115.p20" n="5" corresp="c6115.C.15.c3.5">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.104">6.1.01.104</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.11" from="t.6.1.11.54">6.1.11.54</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.26" from="t.6.1.26.b4">6.1.26.b4</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.28" from="t.6.1.28.8">6.1.28.8</xref></note>
If oil is poured inside the shaft of a sceptre, no one would know.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c4" type="proverb" n="15.c4"><p id="t6115.p21" n="6" corresp="c6115.C.15.c4.6">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.14" from="t.6.1.14.55">6.1.14.55</xref></note>
The stranger is leader in a foreign city.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c5" type="proverb" n="15.c5"><p id="t6115.p22" n="7-9" corresp="c6115.C.15.c5.7">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.14" from="t.6.1.14.56">6.1.14.56</xref></note>
<gap extent="3 lines fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c6" type="proverb" n="15.c6"><p id="t6115.p23" n="10-12" corresp="c6115.C.15.c6.10">
&X;&X; <w type="DN">Enlil's</w> temple, his things are counted. To his things that have been counted (?), let nothing be added. Let their names be destroyed.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c7" type="proverb" n="15.c7"><p id="t6115.p24" n="13" corresp="c6115.C.15.c7.13">
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c8" type="proverb" n="15.c8"><p id="t6115.p25" n="14" corresp="c6115.C.15.c8.14">
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c9" type="proverb" n="15.c9"><p id="t6115.p26" n="15" corresp="c6115.C.15.c9.15">
He who carries water &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c10" type="proverb" n="15.c10"><p id="t6115.p27" n="16" corresp="c6115.C.15.c10.16">
The dishonest man &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c11" type="proverb" n="15.c11"><p id="t6115.p28" n="17" corresp="c6115.C.15.c11.17">
That which rises high &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c12" type="proverb" n="15.c12"><p id="t6115.p29" n="18-19" corresp="c6115.C.15.c12.18">
<gap extent="2 lines fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c13" type="proverb" n="15.c13"><p id="t6115.p30" n="20" corresp="c6115.C.15.c13.20">
A cat for its being a cat; a mongoose for doing what it does.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c14" type="proverb" n="15.c14"><p id="t6115.p31" n="21-22" corresp="c6115.C.15.c14.21">
The rising waters rose one and a half cubits. The water was three cubits high on the quay; it covered his feet with water.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c15" type="proverb" n="15.c15"><p id="t6115.p32" n="23-24" corresp="c6115.C.15.c15.23">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: IM 62823 Seg. B l. 10</xref></note>
The <w type="WN">Tigris</w> is a duck, the <w type="WN">Euphrates</w> is a goose. The king should not come near, &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.15.c16" type="proverb" n="15.c16"><p id="t6115.p33" n="25" corresp="c6115.C.15.c16.25">
